It is true it is a favourite word with the astronomer Geminus (contained in Petavius’ Uranoloyion)‚ but he uses it quite generally of the varying length of the day &a 3 cf. p. 26 Β ἀκολουθεῖ δὲ τούτῳ καὶ παραλλαγὴν τῶν ἡμερῶν μεγά- λην γίνεσθαι διὰ τὴν τῶν τμημάτων ὑπεροχὴν ὧν φέρεται ὃ ἥλιος ὑπὲρ γῆν (ίθ. the length of the day varies according to the sun's elevation). Other instances are cited by Gebser p. 83. We may therefore take the word to express the contrast between the natural sun, which varies its position in the sky from hour to hour and month to mouth, and the eternal Source of all light. A similar contrast is found in Epict.
